<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
This species is easy to recognise by the short apical lobes on the 10th tergite of the male and cerci clearly upcurved and with a lateral spine. The most closely-related species is 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. africana" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="africana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. africana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which, however, has much longer lobes of the 10th abdominal tergite and more robust cerci.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poreuomena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poreuomena" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Poreuomena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with narrow tegmina surpassed by the alae by a few mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 62–64" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 62 - 64. Morphological details of male Poreuomena huxleyi. Habitus (62), lateral view on apex (63), stridulatory area (64)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures62-64" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499191" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">62</figureCitation>
). Stridulatory area marked brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 62–64" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 62 - 64. Morphological details of male Poreuomena huxleyi. Habitus (62), lateral view on apex (63), stridulatory area (64)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures62-64" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499191" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">64</figureCitation>
). Two spines are present on the ventral margin of the hind femora. The apical lobes of the 10th tergite are short and square, separated widely (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 62–64" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 62 - 64. Morphological details of male Poreuomena huxleyi. Habitus (62), lateral view on apex (63), stridulatory area (64)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures62-64" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499191" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">63</figureCitation>
); the cerci are in- and downcurved, dorso-ventrally flattened in the apical portion where a lateral spine is present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="colour">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Colour.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. huxleyi" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huxleyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. huxleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is brownish coloured, with green tegmina and hind tibiae; a black marking is typical at the base of the tegmina and some small black spots on the posterior margin of the tegmina.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
